[3]
Date: Fri 28 May 2010
From: Preben Willeberg
<pwilleberg@ucdavis.edu>


Re: Foot & mouth disease - Japan (16): (MZ) update (item 1, Japan's
follow-up report No 6)
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Just to make a small correction to the moderator's comment regarding
"vaccination to cull" [The comment was: "The "vaccination to cull"
currently applied in Japan, meant to enable completion of stamping
out while preventing virus spread, is a unique, novel procedure which
is not included among the control measures described in OIE's
International Animal Health Code].

"Vaccination to cull" is in fact mentioned as an option in the OIE
Terrestrial Animal Health Code, article 8.5.45, point 2 [A file was
attached].

--
Preben Willeberg, DVM, PhD, Dr. Vet. Sc., Dr. Vet. Sc.h.c., Dipl. ECVPH
Senior Veterinary Global Health Specialist
Center for Animal Disease Modeling and Surveillance (CADMS)
School of Veterinary Medicine, UC Davis
Davis, CA 95616
USA
<pwilleberg@ucdavis.edu>

[Prof Willeberg's corrective observation is fully and gratefully acknowledged.

Indeed, as he indicated, OIE's code includes, in article 8.5.45., the
following strategy to eradicate FMD virus infection following an
outbreak (point 2 out of 4 recognised strategies); see at
<http://oie.int/eng/normes/mcode/en_chapitre_1.8.5.htm>):

"2. slaughter of all clinically affected and in-contact susceptible
animals and vaccination of at-risk animals, with subsequent slaughter
of vaccinated animals." Japan regards, apparently, all susceptible
animals within a 10 km zone around each outbreak as at-risk,
therefore vaccinated.

According to article 8.5.8. ("Recovery of free status"), an FMD free
country or zone, where vaccination is not practised (such as Japan),
can apply for the reinstatement of its freedom from FMD, "3 months
after the slaughter of all vaccinated animals where a stamping-out
policy, emergency vaccination and serological surveillance are
applied in accordance with Articles 8.5.40. to 8.5.46."
- Mod.AS]
